2500|$|Coverholders allow Lloyd's syndicates {{to operate}} in a region or country {{as if they were}} a local insurer. This is {{achieved}} by Lloyd's syndicates delegating their underwriting authority to coverholders. A <b>coverholder</b> can have full or limited authority to underwrite on behalf of a Lloyd's syndicate. It will usually issue the insurance documentation and will often handle claims. [...] The document setting out the terms of the coverholder's delegated authority is known as a binding authority.|$|E
50|$|In April 2016 AXA {{unveiled}} {{a partnership with}} Lloyd's of London insurer Chaucer Holdings to enter the growing market of speciality insurance in Africa. AXA Africa Specialty Risks helps to mitigate risks through its <b>coverholder,</b> Chaucer Syndicate 1084 and AXA Africa Specialty Risks 6130.|$|E
50|$|Coverholders allow Lloyd's syndicates {{to operate}} in a region or country {{as if they were}} a local insurer. This is {{achieved}} by Lloyd's syndicates delegating their underwriting authority to coverholders. A <b>coverholder</b> can have full or limited authority to underwrite on behalf of a Lloyd's syndicate. It will usually issue the insurance documentation and will often handle claims. The document setting out the terms of the coverholder's delegated authority is known as a binding authority.|$|E
25|$|<b>Coverholders</b> are an {{important}} source of business for Lloyd's. Their numbers have grown steadily in recent years, and in 2015 there were 4,008, producing an increasingly meaningful share of the market's overall income. The balance of Lloyd's business is distributed around the world through a network of brokers.|$|R

